This was a heavy concept (Visitor + Double Dispatch) — but honestly, once you “see it right”, it becomes very simple.

I’ll simplify it so you can:

💡 Understand clearly

🧠 Explain in interview

⚙️ Implement without confusion

🧠 1️⃣ Problem (Why Visitor Exists)

You already saw this:

class Room {
    getPrice()
    maintain()
    reserve()
}
❌ Problems
1. Class keeps growing
Room → 3 methods → 10 → 50 → 💥 messy
2. Every new operation → modify class
Add feature → change Room → retest everything
🎯 Core Idea (Visitor)
Move operations OUT of the class
🔥 Final Mental Model
Object = Data
Visitor = Operations
🧩 2️⃣ Structure (Super Simple)
Step 1: Element (Data Holder)
interface Room {
    void accept(RoomVisitor visitor);
}
Step 2: Concrete Elements
class SingleRoom implements Room {
    public void accept(RoomVisitor visitor) {
        visitor.visit(this);
    }
}

class DoubleRoom implements Room {
    public void accept(RoomVisitor visitor) {
        visitor.visit(this);
    }
}
Step 3: Visitor Interface (Operations)
interface RoomVisitor {
    void visit(SingleRoom room);
    void visit(DoubleRoom room);
}
Step 4: Concrete Visitors
💰 Pricing
class PricingVisitor implements RoomVisitor {
    public void visit(SingleRoom room) {
        System.out.println("Single room price = 1000");
    }

    public void visit(DoubleRoom room) {
        System.out.println("Double room price = 2000");
    }
}
🛠️ Maintenance
class MaintenanceVisitor implements RoomVisitor {
    public void visit(SingleRoom room) {
        System.out.println("Maintain single room");
    }

    public void visit(DoubleRoom room) {
        System.out.println("Maintain double room");
    }
}
Step 5: Client
Room room = new SingleRoom();

room.accept(new PricingVisitor());
room.accept(new MaintenanceVisitor());
🔁 3️⃣ Flow (VERY IMPORTANT)
Call:
room.accept(visitor)
Inside accept:
visitor.visit(this)

👉 This is the MAGIC

⚡ 4️⃣ Double Dispatch (Simplified)
❌ Normal (Single Dispatch)
room.accept(visitor);

👉 Decides method based on:

only room type

✅ Visitor (Double Dispatch)
visitor.visit(room);

👉 Decides method based on:

1️⃣ Visitor type (Pricing / Maintenance)
2️⃣ Room type (Single / Double)
🔥 Meaning
Method = f(Visitor Type + Element Type)
🧠 Easy Example
Visitor	Room	Method Called
Pricing	SingleRoom	visit(SingleRoom)
Pricing	DoubleRoom	visit(DoubleRoom)
Maintenance	SingleRoom	visit(SingleRoom)

👉 That’s double dispatch

🎯 5️⃣ Why It Solves Problem
✅ Add new operation → NO class change
Add CleaningVisitor → Done ✅
Room class untouched
✅ No class bloat
Room = clean
Visitors = grow
✅ Open/Closed Principle
Open for extension
Closed for modification
❌ Tradeoff (IMPORTANT)
❌ Adding new element is HARD
Add new room type → update ALL visitors ❌

👉 So:

Visitor is good when:
✔ Elements are stable
✔ Operations keep changing
🆚 Visitor vs Strategy (CONFUSION KILLER)
Strategy
Change HOW something is done (algorithm)

Example:

Payment → UPI / Card / Netbanking
Visitor
Add WHAT to do (operations)

Example:

Room → Pricing / Maintenance / Reserve
🔥 Difference
Strategy = interchangeable behavior  
Visitor = adding new operations
🧠 Interview Answer (Perfect)
Visitor pattern is a behavioral design pattern that allows adding new operations to existing object structures without modifying those objects, by separating operations into visitor classes and using double dispatch.
🚀 When to Use

Use Visitor when:

✔ Many operations on same object
✔ Object structure is stable
✔ Operations keep increasing
✔ Want clean separation
🧠 Memory Trick
“Object holds data, Visitor does work”
🔥 Final Visualization
Before:
Room → 10 methods ❌

After:
Room → accept()
Visitors → all operations ✅